					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Paper codex of the 16th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="chart">
								<support>Paper codex. </support>
								<extent>254 folios<dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>298</height>
										<width>203</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>254 folios (+ 2 unfoliated paper flyleaves at the beginning and at the end).</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>25 quires of mostly 10 leaves each.</p>
									<p>The quires are signed with Hebrew letters on the first and the last page. </p>
									<p>Leaves numbered with Hebrew letters.</p>
								</collation>
								<condition>
									<p>Folios 249-254 are not fully preserved.</p>
								</condition>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1" ruledLines="26" writtenLines="26">
									<p>Masorah magna occupies generally one to four lines in the lower and one to three lines in the upper margin of the page. </p>
									<p>A number of masoretic notes is given at the end of each book. </p>
									<p>All the books except Judges, commence a new page. </p>
									<p>The beginning and the end of the Hafṭarot are indicated in the margin. An annual cycle for the complete Bible is also noted in various places. </p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="1">
							<summary> Yemenite square script, punctuated. <name type="person" role="scribe">Yosef ben Zekharyah ben Me'oded ben Se'adyah al-Kaisi</name>; inscribed with his name in the colophon, folio 254r, with an uncertain date of <date calendar="Seleucid">1900</date>. The same person also punctuated the whole manuscript. </summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="patron">Se'adyah ben David ben Zekharyah ben Amram al-Akhlufi</name>; inscribed with his name in the colophon, folio 254r. </p>
						</additions>
